'''Nadezhda Prokofyevna Suslova''' ({{lang-ru|Надежда Прокофьевна Суслова}}; 1843–1918) was Russia's first [[Women in medicine|female physician]] and a sister of [[Polina Suslova]].<ref>{{cite book|last= Knapp|first=Liza |title=Dostoevsky's The Idiot: a critical companion |year=1998|publisher=[[Northwestern University Press]]|isbn=978-0-8101-1533-0|page=10}}</ref><ref name="slovari"/> She worked as a [[gynecologist]] in [[Nizhny Novgorod]], was involved in many [[Charity (practice)|charity]] efforts.<ref name="lechebnik"/>

== Biography ==
=== Early life ===
Nadezhda was born in Panino village, [[Nizhny Novgorod]] [[guberniya]].<ref name="slovari">(Russian) {{cite book|title=Deyateli revolyutsionnogo dvizheniya v Rossii: Bibliographic Dictionary|url= http://slovari.yandex.ru/~%D0%BA%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%B8/%D0%A0%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8E%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%8B/%D0%A1%D1%83%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B0%20%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B0%20%D0%9F%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%BE%D1%84%D1%8C%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%BD%D0%B0/|date=1927-1934|publisher=Izd-vo Vsesoyuznogo obshestva politicheskih katorzhan i ssylno-poselentsev|location=slovari.[[yandex.ru]]|chapter=Nadezhda Prokofyevna Suslova}}</ref> Her father was [[Sheremetev|the Sheremetevs]]'s [[Serfdom in Russia|serf]], but was able to succeed as a [[merchant]] and [[manufacturer]]. He decided to give a proper education to his daughters, Polina (a [[diminutive form]] of the [[given name]] Apollinaria) and Nadezhda. At home they had a [[governess]], and a dancing teacher.<ref name="vokrug">{{cite journal|last=Nevskaya|first=Elena|date=February 2003|title=Sense and sensibility|journal=[[Vokrug sveta]]|issue=2 |volume=40|issn=0321-0669|url=http://www.vokrugsveta.ru/vs/article/454/|language=Russian}}</ref> Later she entered Penichkau [[Boarding school]] in [[Moscow]], where she learned several foreign languages. Like other young people at that time, Nadezhda was fond of reading, enjoyed the works of [[Nikolay Chernyshevsky]] and [[Nikolay Dobrolyubov|Dobrolyubov]]<ref name="lechebnik"/> and befriended revolutionary democrats. In 1859 the Suslov sisters moved to [[Saint Petersburg]]. In 1861 her short stories ''Rasskaz v pismah'' ({{lang-ru|Рассказ в письмах}}) and ''Fantazyorka'' ({{lang-ru|Фантазёрка}}) were published in ''[[Sovremennik]]''. In the 1860s Nadezhda Suslova joined [[revolutionary]] organization [[Land and Liberty (Russia)|Land and Liberty]].

=== Career ===
She was allowed by [[Ivan Sechenov|Sechenov]] and [[Sergey Botkin|Botkin]] to attended classes at the [[Kirov Military Medical Academy]].<ref name="lechebnik"/> Her first article ''Changes in skin sensations under the influence of electrical stimulation'' was published in ''Meditsinskiy Vestnik'' in 1862. In 1864, after women were officially banned from universities, she moved to [[Switzerland]] and graduated from the [[University of Zurich]].<ref name="lechebnik"/><ref name="slovari"/> Suslova was the first Russian woman to be awarded a [[Doctor of Medicine]] degree (1867)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zhuk|first=Sergei|date=Winter 2001|title=Science, Women and Revolution in Russia |journal=[[Bulletin of the History of Medicine]] |volume=75 |issue=4|pages=802–803 |issn=0007-5140 |doi=10.1353/bhm.2001.0204|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/bulletin_of_the_history_of_medicine/v075/75.4zhuk.html}}</ref> as a [[surgeon]]/[[obstetrician]]. In 1867 she married [[Friedrich Erismann]] and with him returned to Saint Petersburg, where she had to pass the exams again and defend her [[diploma]] for the second time.

